{"title_page": "David Lipsey, Baron Lipsey", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n[[File:official portrait of Lord Lipsey crop 2.jpg|thumb]]\n'''David Lawrence Lipsey, Baron Lipsey''' (born 21 April 1948) is a British journalist and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician.\n\nAfter attending [[Bryanston School]], Dorset (1962\u201367),<ref>[http://www.davidlipsey.co.uk/biography-cv/ Online autobiography]</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Lipsey |first1=David |title=In the Corridors of Power: An Autobiography |date=2012 |publisher=Biteback Publishing |location=London |isbn=9781849544290 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HoO1AwAAQBAJ |accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref> Lipsey won an Exhibition in [[Politics, Philosophy and Economics]] (PPE) at [[Magdalen College, Oxford]] in 1968 and graduated with a First Class degree, winning the University Gibbs Prize in Politics in 1969. He went on to become a political adviser to [[Anthony Crosland]] in Opposition and an adviser to 10 Downing Street. He has worked as a journalist for a variety of different publications including the [[Sunday Times]], [[Sunday Correspondent]], [[The Times]], [[The Guardian]] and [[The Economist]]. From 1982 to 1983 he was Chairman of the [[Fabian Society]] and from 1970 to 1972 Secretary of the Streatham Labour Party.\n\nDavid Lipsey was awarded a Special [[Orwell Prize]] in 1997 for his work as \u2018Bagehot\u2019 in The Economist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theorwellprize.co.uk/?s=lipsey|title=Lord Lipsey \u2013 The Orwell Prize|last=|first=|date=|website=www.theorwellprize.co.uk|publisher=|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n\nLipsey has held numerous senior posts in public life. As well as his economic and social interests, he chairs the All Party Parliamentary group on Classical Music (from 2011), is a patron of the Glasbury Arts Festival, a trustee of the Cambrian Orchestra Trust and chairman of the [[Sidney Nolan|Sidney Nolan Trust]] (from 2011), as well as being a trustee of other arts organisations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-lipsey/2492|title=Lord Lipsey|website=UK Parliament|language=en|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref> Lipsey was created a [[Life peer]] as '''Baron Lipsey''', of [[Tooting Bec]] in the [[London Borough of Wandsworth]], on 30 July 1999.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55572 |date=4 August 1999 |page=8409}}</ref> He sits on the Labour benches in the House of Lords.\n\nHis sporting interests have included harness racing and presidency of the British Harness Racing Club (2008 to 2016) as well as chairmanship of the British Greyhound Racing Board (now the [[Greyhound Board of Great Britain]]) from 2004 to 2009.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* http://biographies.parliament.uk/parliament/default.asp?id=26939\n* http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-david-lipsey\n* http://lordsoftheblog.wordpress.com/the-authors/\n* https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1351595/Life-in-the-Lords-is-too-tough-says-Labour-peer.html\n* [http://archives.lse.ac.uk/TreeBrowse.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&field=RefNo&key=LIPSEY Catalogue of the Lipsey papers held at LSE Archives]\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Chair of the [[Fabian Society]]|years=1981 &ndash; 1982|before=[[Shirley Williams]]|after=[[Stella Meldram]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Fabian Society}}\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lipsey, David}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bryanston School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Magdalen College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Chairs of the Fabian Society]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:People in greyhound racing]]\n\n\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n{{Life-peer-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=September 2016}}\n[[File:official portrait of Lord Lipsey crop 2.jpg|thumb]]\n'''David Lawrence Lipsey, Baron Lipsey''' (born 21 April 1948) is a British journalist and [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour Party]] politician.\n\nAfter attending [[Bryanston School]], Dorset (1962 -67)<ref>[http://www.davidlipsey.co.uk/biography-cv/ Online autobiography]</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Lipsey |first1=David |title=In the Corridors of Power: An Autobiography |date=2012 |publisher=Biteback Publishing |location=London |isbn=9781849544290 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HoO1AwAAQBAJ |accessdate=6 August 2019}}</ref>, Lipsey won an Exhibition in [[Politics, Philosophy and Economics]] (PPE) at [[Magdalen College, Oxford]] in 1968 and graduated with a First Class degree, winning the University Gibbs Prize in Politics in 1969. He went on to become a political adviser to [[Anthony Crosland]] in Opposition and an adviser to 10 Downing Street. He has worked as a journalist for a variety of different publications including the [[Sunday Times]], [[Sunday Correspondent]], [[The Times]], [[The Guardian]] and [[The Economist]]. From 1982 to 1983 he was Chairman of the [[Fabian Society]] and from 1970 to 1972 Secretary of the Streatham Labour Party.\n\nDavid Lipsey was awarded a Special [[Orwell Prize]] in 1997 for his work as \u2018Bagehot\u2019 in The Economist.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theorwellprize.co.uk/?s=lipsey|title=Lord Lipsey \u2013 The Orwell Prize|last=|first=|date=|website=www.theorwellprize.co.uk|publisher=|language=en-GB|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref>\n\nLipsey has held numerous senior posts in public life. As well as his economic and social interests, he chairs the All Party Parliamentary group on Classical Music (from 2011), is a patron of the Glasbury Arts Festival, a trustee of the Cambrian Orchestra Trust and chairman of the [[Sidney Nolan|Sidney Nolan Trust]] (from 2011), as well as being a trustee of other arts organisations.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.parliament.uk/biographies/lords/lord-lipsey/2492|title=Lord Lipsey|website=UK Parliament|language=en|access-date=2017-02-01}}</ref> Lipsey was created a [[Life peer]] as '''Baron Lipsey''', of [[Tooting Bec]] in the [[London Borough of Wandsworth]], on 30 July 1999.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=55572 |date=4 August 1999 |page=8409}}</ref> He sits on the Labour benches in the House of Lords.\n\nHis sporting interests have included harness racing and presidency of the British Harness Racing Club (2008 to 2016) as well as chairmanship of the British Greyhound Racing Board (now the [[Greyhound Board of Great Britain]]) from 2004 to 2009.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==Sources==\n* http://biographies.parliament.uk/parliament/default.asp?id=26939\n* http://hansard.millbanksystems.com/people/mr-david-lipsey\n* http://lordsoftheblog.wordpress.com/the-authors/\n* https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1351595/Life-in-the-Lords-is-too-tough-says-Labour-peer.html\n* [http://archives.lse.ac.uk/TreeBrowse.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&field=RefNo&key=LIPSEY Catalogue of the Lipsey papers held at LSE Archives]\n\n{{start box}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{succession box|title=Chair of the [[Fabian Society]]|years=1981 &ndash; 1982|before=[[Shirley Williams]]|after=[[Stella Meldram]]}}\n{{end box}}\n\n{{Fabian Society}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lipsey, David}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bryanston School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Magdalen College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Chairs of the Fabian Society]]\n[[Category:Labour Party (UK) life peers]]\n[[Category:British male journalists]]\n[[Category:People in greyhound racing]]\n{{UK-journalist-stub}}\n{{Life-peer-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/David_Lipsey,_Baron_Lipsey"}
